> We've made it easy for you to recreate this all-American family favourite in just six simple steps. These hearty open sandwiches are made by piling high ground tomato bbq beef mince inside a grilled ciabatta bun, topped with crunchy lettuce and cheese. Fun and delicious but as the name suggests things can get a little messy - so make sure you have lots of napkins!

Heat a splash of @oil{} in a large #frying pan{} on medium heat. Once hot, add the @British Beef Mince{240%g} and @Easy Garlic{1/2}. Cook until browed breaking it up with a #wooden spoon{}, ~{5%minutes}.

Trim the ends from the @Carrot{1}(trimmed), then grate on a #coarse grater{} (no need to peel!). Add half the carrot and the @Tomato Puree{15%g} to the pan. Cook for ~{2%minutes}.

Add the @Tomato Passata{1/2}, @BBQ Sauce{16%g} and @Water{50%ml}. Reduce the heat and simmer until thick, ~{12-15%minutes}.

Meanwhile, trim the @Baby Gem Lettuce{1} then half lengthways and slice widthways. Juice the @Lemon{1/2} and add both to a large #mixing bowl{} with the @Mayonnaise{1}, remaining carrot and a pinch of @salt{pinch} and @pepper{pinch}. Mix well to combine and taste to check for seasoning.

Preheat the #grill{} to high.

Halve the @Ciabatta{1} lengthways (as if you were making a sandwich) and place on a #baking tray{}. Drizzle with oil and grill until golden, ~{2-3%minutes}. Remove (leave the grill on, we will use it again).

Once the beef mix has thickened up, season to taste with salt and pepper and remove from the heat. Pile the beef on each slice of ciabatta and tear the @Mozzarella{1/2} over the top. Return the loaded ciabattas to the grill until melted, bubbling and slightly coloured, ~{3-5%minutes}.

Place one sloppy joe ciabatta onto each #plate{}, and add a pile of slaw on the side.

Serve up. Enjoy!